Hurricane Rosa threatens floods in Phoenix, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City (areas where droughts may benefit)
It’s not common for a tropical low-pressure furrow to hit Arizona, but that’s exactly what’s likely to happen early next week when the remaining energy of Hurricane Rosa crosses the desert southwest and carries the risk of torrential flooding.
The National Weather Service has already issued flood warnings for Monday and Tuesday from western Arizona for southern and eastern Nevada, southeastern California, and Utah, including cities like Phoenix, Flagstaff, Las Vegas, and Salt Lake City.
Rosa is expected to take a direct route through Phoenix on Tuesday and bring rain on Monday evening.
The National Weather Service of Phoenix said on Twitter that “since 1950, only ten tropical cyclones have retained tropical storm or pressure status within 200 miles of Phoenix!
Katrina (1967) was a hurricane still 64 km from the Arizona border."
The latest models of the National Hurricane Center predict rainfall of 50 to 100 mm, in the Mogollon Rim region of Arizona at points of up to 150 mm.
In other areas of the desert northwest, including the center of the Rocky Mountains and the Great Basin, it is likely to fall 25 to 50 mm, with local totals up to 100 mm.
For those who are not in danger of flooding, dew rain can be a blessing as the area has been hit by drought.
Flooding is a very serious matter, but maybe it will help somewhere, because the southwestern United States has just been hit by a drought.
Weather.com reports that according to the U.S. Drought Monitor, more than 40 percent of Arizona experiences at least “extreme drought,” the second-highest category.
The path of Hurricane Rosa will first lead to the Baja California Peninsula in Mexico.
Rosa, still hurricane-force with a maximum wind speed of 137 km/h, will be 620 km south of Punta Eugenia, Mexico on Sunday morning and will move at 19 km/h north.
Then the storm meets the colder waters of the Pacific Ocean, and thus loses strength.
It is expected to arrive in Mexico on Monday afternoon or evening as a tropical storm.
In some parts of Mexico, rainfall will be strong, posing a high risk of flooding.
"A total of 75 to 150 mm of precipitation is expected in the area from Baja California to northwest Sonor, and may occur as high as 250 mm," weather.com said.
Rosa then travels like a tropical storm through Mexico to the north and arrives at the Arizona border early Tuesday morning, then passes through Arizona and enters southern Utah late Tuesday night.
"The main risk for Rosa or her remains is expected to be very heavy rainfall in Baja California, northwest Sonora and the desert southwest of the US," the National Hurricane Center reports.
