U.S. to double funding for artificial intelligence
According to investor and artificial intelligence expert Kai-Fu Lee, who worked for Google, Microsoft and Apple, China is increasingly active in the field of artificial intelligence (AI), and the US should double the amount it spends on research in this area.
The comment comes after various parts of the U.S. government published AI announcements, even though the U.S. as a whole has no formal strategy for artificial intelligence.
China, meanwhile, last year implemented a plan to be number one in AI innovation by 2030.
“A doubling of the AI research budget would be a good start given that all other countries are much further away than the US and we are looking for another breakthrough in AI,” Lee says.
Lee said in an interview with CNBC this week that doubling funding could double the chance that the next big AI discovery will be made in the US.
Lee, who published his book “AI superpowers: China, Silicon Valley and the New World Order” at Houghton Mifflin Harcourt this month, is CEO of Sinovation Ventures, which has invested in one of China’s most prominent AI companies, Face++.
At Carnegie Mellon University in the 1980s, he worked on an AI system that surpassed the best American player in Othello, and later was a senior Microsoft research officer and president of the Chinese branch of Google.
Lee praised previous U.S. government technology competitions, such as the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency's Robotic Challenge, and asked when the next one would help identify new visionaries.
Researchers in the U.S. often have to work hard to get government grants, Lee said.
“Academic leaders are not being taken away by China, but by corporations,” Lee said.
In recent years, Facebook, Google and other technology companies have employed the best experts from universities to work on artificial intelligence.
Changes in immigration policy could also help improve AI efforts, Lee said.
“In my opinion, AI PhD holders should automatically be offered green cards,” he says.
The State Council of China released a New Generation Artificial Intelligence Development Plan in July 2017.
China’s National Science Foundation provides funding to people in academic institutions in a similar way as the National Science Council and other government organizations give money to researchers in the U.S., but the quality of academic work is poorer in China, Lee says.
The U.S. Department of Defense has set up a Joint Center for Artificial Intelligence this year to engage industry and academic partners, and the White House has announced the creation of an AI Select Committee.
And DARPA announced this month that it is investing $2 billion in an initiative called AI Next.
NSF invests more than $100 million a year in AI research.
