Macedonians vote in referendum on whether to change the name of the country
The people of Macedonia voted in a referendum on Sunday to change the country's name to "Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that blocks applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia and claims that the name of its northern neighbor represents a claim to its territory, and therefore has vetoed Macedonia's accession to NATO and the EU.
The two governments struck a deal in June on a proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change will weaken the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum, and a campaign calling for a boycott has raised questions about whether at least 50 percent of voters will turn out to be needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question in the referendum was: “Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with an agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the successor countries to the former Yugoslavia, to join organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the roof of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” says 79-year-old Olivera Georgiyevska from Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough members of parliament have said they will follow the result of the vote.
A change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said no problems were reported until 1 p.m.
However, voter turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters finally cast their vote.
“I went to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their votes in a Macedonian referendum on a name change that would open the country's way to NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepares a small podium and pulls up chairs in front of tents erected by people who boycott the referendum.
“We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to enter them with our heads held high, not the door for the servants,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have pride.
If they don’t want us like Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I think a large majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after voting.
A “yes” would be a “confirmation of our future.”
According to a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Research, between 30 and 43 percent of voters could take part in the referendum - less than the required turnout.
Another poll, conducted by Macedonian television station Telma TV, found that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent said they would vote yes.
For a referendum to be successful, 50 percent plus one voter must participate.
The failure of the referendum would mark the first serious blow to the pro-Western government’s policies since it took office last May.
