It started shortly after Jeremy became the leader, and colleagues I once thought had similar political views suddenly expected me to turn 180 degrees and hold positions that I otherwise could not agree with, whether national security or the EU’s single market.
Whenever I speak in public - and it doesn't matter what I say - there is a tirade of swearing on social media, calling for my dismissal, denouncing the politics of the centre and telling me I shouldn't be in the Labour Party.
And it's not just my experience.
I know I’m more fortunate than some of my colleagues because comments directed at me are usually political.
I respect the professionalism and commitment of those colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never back down.
One aspect of this era of politics that I am most disappointed with is how insults become the norm.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should cultivate a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that diverse stream of opinion, and with every motion of censure or change in the rules of choice, the party becomes more limited.
Over the past two years, I’ve been advised many times to hold back, not to speak up so much, and then “I’ll be fine.”
But that's not why I went into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a school pupil, provoked by the negligence of Margaret Thatcher’s government, which has literally disintegrated my general-school class, I have been struggling to fight for better public services for those who need them most, whether as a local councillor or government minister.
I never hid my politics, not even in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be surprised at my political positions and areas where I disagree with the current leadership.
To those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would only say that as the country struggles towards Brexit, which will damage households, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
However, my main message is not to the Moment in Nottingham, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour Party members or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threats of appeal or political pragmatism will deter me from doing what I believe is in the best interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
