Throughout inland Bolivia, there is still a vivid memory of the coast the country lost to Chile in the bloody 19th-century war for resources - as well as the desire to re-enter the Pacific Ocean.
These aspirations are perhaps the greatest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice, which is expected to fall on October 1 after five years of negotiations.
“Bolivia has energy, a spirit of unity and calm and of course expects a positive result,” Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla said.
Many Bolivians will watch the MSD's decisions on big screens across the country with the hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after many decades of intermittent talks, Chile is obliged to negotiate that it will grant Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president Evo Morales - who faces a controversial re-election battle next year - is also keen on Monday's decision.
“We are very close to going back to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia's favor - and even if it did, not much would change.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no power to award Chilean territory to anyone, and has said it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the ICD’s decision comes just six months after the last arguments were made shows that the case “wasn’t complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
