“The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian government,” says Zarate.
He adds that Morales' offensive rhetoric has weakened any remaining goodwill for Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will start acting again one day, but after this it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance “to end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - used the question of the sea as a political crutch.
