John Edward: Language skills are a must for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have had a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent exam results. Individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities underline this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and working to ensure the best possible level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the careers they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still popular and in demand subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart."
It is a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s exams show that languages are at the top of the charts, with independent schools having the highest success rates.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved the highest A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by pupils are as important in the study plans of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17 per cent of job vacancies are under-skilled.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalised world.
Whichever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them failed to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, namely 15 percent, being French.
That is why it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially the languages of emerging economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school is different in the languages it teaches.
A number of schools are focusing on more classic modern languages, while others are teaching languages considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages are vital to the country’s future in the global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be seen as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
