North Korea says it will not “under any circumstances” disarm unilaterally and without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister said on Saturday that continued UN sanctions had deepened their distrust of the United States and under such circumstances the country would never give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told his annual general assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
“We don’t see a proper response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances, it is impossible to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for every step taken, his statements appeared significant in that he did not reject unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had gone through it in the past.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees of North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks a formal end to the 1950-1953 war conflict, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the pressure on sanctions to enforce their targets, and even objects to a ‘declaration of end of war,’” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the dream of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader highlighted at the UN earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea and not the US were on the sidelines of this denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a standoff.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s targeting of U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump branded Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations last year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but said much work must be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is completely denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have the time frame to do so, saying: “If it takes two years, three years or five months - it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must continue vigorously and unceasingly until we recognize a complete, final, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously supported sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to curb financing of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
