Harvard students attend a course designed to teach them how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has forced all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of macho study all night long, when students do not sleep and encourage themselves with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most renowned university are often baffled when it comes to the basics of self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you just telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was introduced for the first time this year, explains to students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performances and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university had decided to implement the course after finding that the students were seriously sleepless during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of student dormitories where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of proper sleeping habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that students’ behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking," added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” for fighting stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, leaving one still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course one of his classes took during his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the whole course.
It hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can upset your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
