This was the first time the Navy returned the ship to the manufacturer after handover.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of major "software errors and defects on metal elements" defects that would render the warship unusable for use in combat.
Software failures were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttember-class vessel would be operated by a crew of some 120 sailors - half the personnel needed on the Bremen-class frigates.
It has also been shown to have considerable excess weight, reducing its performance and limiting the Navy's ability to add future innovation.
It is believed that the 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfal will be twice as heavy as similar class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
