National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research is underway at a bat housing estate in the Highlands of Scotland to uncover how bats are using the landscape to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings of the research will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future activities for the conservation of this species.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will track bats whistling and the smallest and brown long and watery at the Inverewe Gardens botanical garden in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key areas in this bat housing estate to monitor bat activity throughout the year.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings detects the frequency of bat calls and what each species does.
Subsequently, a habitat map and a report will be released, which will create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most important to bats, and how individual species use them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and best practice in maintaining forested areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened as a result of the construction and territorial development that affect the colonies and the natural environment.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as fly traps and chemical treatments for building materials and cat attacks can also pose a risk.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes in hunting prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to track bugs and obstacles in flight.
NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has trained professionals who regularly conduct surveys, colony checks, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization has even established the first and only dedicated bat reserve in the Threeve housing estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
