“We have a great area here in Threave for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and the best habitat.
But there's still too much we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to survive."
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before starting real estate maintenance work, as it is possible that the unconscious destruction of one mother's nest can kill up to 400 females and chicks, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish representative of the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages the public to step up and help.
